patterns_on_map.description: Areas filled with white, representing residential zones across the map.
Small areas filled with dark (black) color, scattered within residential and commercial zones, and along main roads.
Areas filled with horizontal lines, primarily seen in block-sized sections, often bordering the river or major arteries.
Large sections filled with diagonal lines (top-left to bottom-right), particularly along the river and railway lines, indicating large industrial areas.
The river (Fox River) is depicted without a specific fill pattern but has contours indicating water flow or depth, and sometimes small islands/banks with horizontal lines or solid fill.
Roads and streets are typically white, contrasting with the outlines of blocks, and some main roads are labeled with text.

additional_notes: The map also includes lot numbers within blocks, ward boundaries, and names of streets and additions. The legend effectively covers the primary land use classifications. The map is black and white, so 'color' refers to grayscale intensity.

map_subject: Zoning regulations and land use districts for the city of Atchison, Kansas

patterns_on_map.description: Sparse dots covering large areas of the map, including residential blocks, Oak Hill Cemetery, Jackson Park, and undeveloped areas along the city limits.
patterns_on_map.likely_meaning: One Family Dwellings or Parks/Civic areas (District A)

patterns_on_map.description: Horizontal lines observed in several blocks, particularly in the central and northern parts of the city.
Crosshatch patterns found in various blocks throughout the map, often near commercial and industrial zones.
Solid black fill used for a significant portion of the city's core, especially along major streets and bordering the Missouri River.
patterns_on_map.likely_meaning: Commercial uses (District D) and Heavy Industry (District F)

patterns_on_map.description: Diagonal lines observed in blocks, often adjacent to commercial or heavy industrial zones.
The entire Missouri River is depicted with a solid black fill.
A very dense, fine diagonal hatching pattern along the immediate bank of the Missouri River.
patterns_on_map.likely_meaning: River bank, shoreline, or specific riverfront development zone, distinct from Light Industry.

patterns_on_map.description: Thin parallel lines indicating railroad tracks, particularly prominent along the river and western parts of the city.
Solid white fill is used for roads, streets, and unbuilt/unspecified plots within zoned blocks.
patterns_on_map.likely_meaning: Roads, streets, unzoned or undeveloped land

additional_notes: Districts D (Commercial) and F (Heavy Industry) share the exact same visual symbol (solid black fill) in this black and white map, making them indistinguishable without external context or color information. The legend also provides detailed height, yard, and lot area regulations for each district.
